<h1>@ViewData["Title"]</h1>

p>The SPHERE VRF system provides decentralized, verifiable randomness without relying on a centralized authority.
It allows clients to request random numbers that can be publicly verified for fairness, making it ideal for games, lotteries, audits, and any system that demands true unpredictability and trustless verification.</p>

<h2>How It Works</h2>

<p>
    When a client requests randomness, the SPHERE network processes the request securely through its decentralized nodes.
    Each step is cryptographically verifiable, ensuring no single party can manipulate the outcome. Here's the general flow:
</p>

<div style="text-align:center;  margin: 30px 0;">
    <pre style="text-align:left; display: inline-block; padding: 20px; background: #f8f9fa; border: 1px solid #ccc; border-radius: 8px; color: #212529;">
Client ➔ Request Random Number
    ↓
System Node ➔ Receives & Validates Request
    ↓
Master Node ➔ Distributes Workload
    ↓
Manager Nodes ➔ Assign Randomness Tasks to Workers
    ↓
Worker Nodes ➔ Independently Generate VRF Proofs
    ↓
Verifier Node ➔ Confirms Proof Authenticity
    ↓
Master Node ➔ Assembles Verified Results
    ↓
System Node ➔ Returns Final Random Number to Client
    ↓
Client ➔ Can Independently Verify the Randomness
    </pre>
</div>

<h2>Key Features</h2>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Decentralized Verification:</strong> No single node controls the outcome — randomness is verified across multiple nodes.</li>
    <li><strong>Cryptographic Proofs:</strong> Each random number includes a verifiable proof that it was generated fairly and correctly.</li>
    <li><strong>Transparent Responses:</strong> Clients can check the results independently — trust is optional, verification is built-in.</li>
    <li><strong>Scalable Architecture:</strong> Requests are divided across managers and workers for high reliability even under heavy load.</li>
</ul>

